What is an AWS Region?
A region is a geographic area containing AWS data centers. AWS has Regions across the globe, letting you choose where to run your applications and store your data.

Selecting a Region
Consider these factors when Choosing a Region:
Compliance
Some regulations require data to stay within specific countries. For example, GDPR requires companies operating in the EU to choose Regions that meet its data protection requirements.

Customer Proximity
Selecting a region near your customers reduces latency and improves their experince. For example, a seattle-based company with Norwegian customers might run infrastructure locally but deploy customer-facing applications in a European Region.

Feature Availability
Not all Regions support all services. AWS constantly expands, but some features may only be available in specific Regions. For Examples, AWS GovCLoud is only available in Regions designed for US government requirements.

Pricing
Costs vary by Region based on operational expenses, taxes and local requirements. You will learn more about pricing in a later chapter.

AWS Cloud Availablity Zones
What is an Avainlability Zone(AZ)?
An Availability zone(AZ) is one or more data centers with a region, each with independent power,networking, and connectivity. Every Regionhas at least three AZs.
AZs are physically separated to reduce disaster risk, yet close enough for low-latency communication between them.

High Availability
Deploy resources across multiple AZs so your application continues running even if one zone fails. This provides:
High availability: Continuous operation without downtime.
Agility:Quick adaptation to changing requirements
Elasticity: Automatic scaling based on demand.


What are AWS Edge Locations?
Aws Edge Location are Strategically placed sites around the world that cache content to deliver data with lower latency. They are smaller facilities outside of standard Regions, Positioned closer to end users.

Amazon CloudFront
Edge Locations use Amazon CloudFront, a content delivery network(CDN), that stores cached copies of your content at locations closer to your users. This results in faster loading times and a better user experience.
CloudeFront Use Cases
Streaming viedo: Viedos play smoothly without buffering, even during peak times
Ecommerce: Product images and pages load quickly during busy shopping seasons.
Mobile apps:Map data and images delivered quickly for responsive experiences.

Caching-How AWS Edge Locations Work
Caching stores copies of frequently accessed data closer to users, reducing the need to fetch data from the origin server every time
1. A user requests content(e.g, an image or viedo)
2. If not cached, the content is fetched from the origin and stored at the edge location
3. Future requests for the same content are served from the nearest Edge Location
Content is Delivered faster because it comes from the Edge Location nearest to the user, not the Origin Server.


