AWS cloud Security
What is cloud Security?
Building and maintaining a secure cloud environment requires protecting data, network and applications from threats. Security in the cloud is a shared responsibility between AWS and its customers.

AWS provides security mechanisms to prevent incidents, protect resources and detect and respond to threats. This section covers the key concepts and services that help protect your cloud resources.

Authentication vs Authorization
Authentication: verifies identity through credentials like username and password. Example: An employee logs in to an employee portal.

Authorization: Determines witch actions a verified user can perform Example: An employee can only access their own records.

AWS Security Controls:AWS offers multiple security mechanisms to protect your cloud resources:
Prevent: Security incidents through proper permission and access management
Protect:Networks, applications,and data
Detect and Respond:To security incidents as they occur

Shared Responsibility Model
What is the Shared Responsibility Model?
The shared responsibility model divides security duties between AWS and you. AWS is responsible for security of the cloud,while you are responsible for security in the cloud.
Think of it this way: AWS secures the building, you secure what's inside your apartment.
Responsibilities
AWS:Security of the cloud
AWS protects the infrastructure running all services:
Physical:Data centers,hardware,networking equipment
Global infrastructure:Regions,Availability zones, Edge locations
Core services:Compute, storage,database, networking
Software:Virtualization and underlying software.

You: Security in the cloud
You are responsible for everything you put in AWS:
Your Data:What you store and how you encrypt it
Access control:Who can access your resources
Configuration:Operating system,network and firewall settings.
Applications: The software you run and how you secure it.

User Permissions and Access
What is AWS identity and Access Management(IAM)?
AWS identity and Access Management(IAM) securely manages identities and access to AWS services. By default, all actions are denied - you must explicitly grant permission.
IAM follows the Principle of least Privilege:Only give people and systems access to what they need. It provides users, groups,roles,and policies to configure access based on your security needs.
IAM Identities
Root User
The account owner created when first start an AWS account with full permissions.Best Practices:
Use a strong password and enable MFA
Avoid using root user for daily tasks
Create IAM identities for daily work

IAM Users
Represents a person or application that interacts with AWS. Created without permissions by default - Create one IAM user per individual.

IAM Policies:
Documents that allow or deny permissions to AWS resources. Customize access for each user based on what they need.

IAM Groups
A collection of IAM users. Policies assigned to a group apply to all users in that group.

IAM Roles
An identity you can assume to gain temporary access to permissions. When assuming a role, you abandon previous permissions and take on the role's permissions. Best for temporary access scenarios.

Multi-factor Authentication (MFA)
Requires at least two verification methods to log in, providing an extra security layer. Can use security codes sent to mobile devices or email.
